    "best_read": "Rip baseline early on the hand cue alone, plant the outside foot, and back-cut hard behind x2 to the front of the rim before x4 finishes the rotation. The lead pass arrives with two seconds to lift — no shot-clock buy-back this time, the game clock is the only clock that matters.",
    "acceptable_reads": [
      "V-cut up to the wing relief — keeps the play alive, but the game clock decides on the next pass and there's no shot-clock buy-back."
    ],
    "bad_reads": [
      "Stand in the corner and call for it — x2's hand deflects, ball out of bounds with 5 left.",
      "Front-cut into the paint — x4 was already rotating; the cut dies and the clock runs."
    ],
    "common_miss_reason": "Players hold the corner spot waiting for the swing because the C&S is the natural finish on a swing-rotation. With the clock under 8, the defender knows the swing is coming and pre-commits to the lane. The cutter has to read that pre-commit and punish it before the clock decides for them.",
    "why_best_read_works": "The denying defender's hand-in-lane stance is closed off to the rim. A baseline back-cut puts the cutter behind the help-side rotation before x4 can rotate up; the lead pass lands at the rim with the shot clock buying the window.",
    "decoder_teaching_point": "Late clock + denial = baseline backdoor. The corner is the only catch the defense can't recover to.",
    "lesson_connection": "backdoor-window",
    "explanation_md": "**End-Clock, Disguised.** D4: the denial is read off the hand alone — the hip arrow is hidden, the cognition window is 300ms tighter, and the only clock is the game clock. You don't get a swing-pass reset. The cue you trusted at D3 is still there; you just have less of it and less time. **Read the hand. Rip early. Cut hard before x4 finishes rotating. Commit before the clock crosses 4.**",
    "feedback": {
      "correct": "Right read at D4. You took the denial off the hand alone, no hip backup, and beat x4 to the rim before the clock decided.",
      "partial": "Relief catch keeps the play alive — but the game clock will decide the next bounce. The disguised denial was the only rim window you get.",
      "wrong": "Read the hand, not the hip. The hip's hidden — the hand is the whole cue."
    },
    "self_review_checklist": [
